## Problem

`startGmailWatcher` reassigns `renewInterval` to a new `setInterval` (line 323) without first clearing the previous handle. If the watcher is restarted (e.g., config reload triggers a new `startGmailWatcher` call), the old interval keeps firing indefinitely alongside the new one.

`stopGmailWatcher` already has the correct cleanup pattern (lines 343-345):
```typescript
if (renewInterval) {
  clearInterval(renewInterval);
  renewInterval = null;
}
```
But `startGmailWatcher` does not replicate this guard before creating a new interval.

## Fix

Add `clearInterval` guard before the `setInterval` call, matching `stopGmailWatcher`'s existing cleanup pattern.

## Real behavior proof
Behavior addressed: the Gmail watcher renewal interval is now cleared before creating a new one, preventing leaked timers on watcher restart.
Real environment tested: local source checkout of openclaw/openclaw at commit 71b79f008d (current upstream/main) on Linux x86_64, Node v26.0.0.
Exact steps or command run after this patch: pnpm tsgo:core (type check); verified the fix matches the existing stopGmailWatcher cleanup pattern at lines 343-345.
Evidence after fix: type check output below.

```
$ pnpm tsgo:core
$ node scripts/run-tsgo.mjs -p tsconfig.core.json --incremental --tsBuildInfoFile .artifacts/tsgo-cache/core.tsbuildinfo
```
No errors.

Code comparison showing the fix matches the existing cleanup pattern:

stopGmailWatcher (existing, lines 343-345):
```typescript
if (renewInterval) {
  clearInterval(renewInterval);
  renewInterval = null;
}
```

startGmailWatcher (added, before setInterval):
```typescript
if (renewInterval) {
  clearInterval(renewInterval);
  renewInterval = null;
}
```

Observed result after fix: type check passes. The fix is a 3-line guard that mirrors the existing cleanup pattern in the same file.
What was not tested: live Gmail watcher restart scenario (would require a configured Gmail hook and config reload). No test file exists for gmail-watcher.ts.
